The paper addresses the problem of applying Task and Motion Planning (TAMP) in real-world environments, which involves combining symbolic and geometric reasoning to produce sequential manipulation plans. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a TAMP algorithm that optimizes over Cartesian frames defined relative to target objects, which involves using perception and control, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Computer Vision (cs.CV), and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. Finally, the paper applies the TAMP framework to a torque-controlled robot in a pick and place setting, which involves learning from data, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
